2026-06-23 20:55:15,567 DEBUG msg #102: UserMessage text: Produce an implementation blueprint for Cycle 1 — Data Foundations of the World Cup 2026 prediction CLI (Python 3.11+, Typer + Pydantic, pandas, requests, pytest) at /Volumes/External SSD/worldcup-2026-prediction. Output a blueprint only — do NOT write code. First read the existing modules under worldcup_playoff/data/ (loader.py, client.py, cleaner.py, builders.py, bracket_builder.py), config.py, cli.py, and the tests/ dir to ground the plan in real conventions.

## Cycle 1 scope (ONLY these; later cycles do Elo/Poisson/features/models/sim — do NOT design those)
1. `worldcup_playoff/data/martj42_loader.py` — no-key loader for martj42/international_results CC0 datasets:
   - results.csv (49,477 rows: `date, home_team, away_team, home_score, away_score, tournament, city, country, neutral`) — coerce `"NA"` scores → nullable Int (pandas Int64), `"TRUE"/"FALSE"` → bool. Map to internal schema `DATE, HOME_TEAM, AWAY_TEAM, HOME_GOALS, AWAY_GOALS, TOURNAMENT, NEUTRAL`. martj42 already contains the WC2026 schedule (tournament == "FIFA World Cup", scores NA until played).
   - shootouts.csv (678 rows: `date, home_team, away_team, winner, first_shooter`)
   - goalscorers.csv (47,741 rows: `date, home_team, away_team, team, scorer, minute, own_goal, penalty`)
   - Base URL: https://raw.githubusercontent.com/martj42/international_results/master/ . Must work with no API key. Consider a local on-disk cache so tests/offline runs don't hit the network.
2. `worldcup_playoff/data/live.py` — live WC2026 adapter reusing the EXISTING `FootballClient` (worldcup_playoff/data/client.py; `get(path, params) -> dict`). Pull `GET /v4/competitions/WC/matches` (104 matches, 44 played; fields id, utcDate, status, stage∈{GROUP_STAGE,LAST_32,LAST_16,QUARTER_FINALS,SEMI_FINALS,THIRD_PLACE,FINAL}, group∈{GROUP_A..GROUP_L}|null, homeTeam{id,name}, awayTeam{id,name}, score{winner,fullTime{home,away}}) and `/standings` (12 groups). Expose "state of tournament as of today": played results, remaining group fixtures, current standings. Knockout slot teams are null until groups resolve.
3. Team-name crosswalk — a normalization dict/function mapping martj42 ↔ football-data.org names (Türkiye/Turkey, Czechia, South Korea, United States/USA, IR Iran, etc.) to a canonical form, so live results join historical data.
4. WC2026 R32 bracket-slotting — encode the official top-2-per-group + 8-best-thirds template and the best-third-place assignment rules so a later-cycle simulator can resolve LAST_32 from final group standings. Data + pure rules, NOT running a simulation.
5. Schema-verification tests for each loader against the exact data-contract shapes.

## Constraints
- Reuse existing FootballClient; do NOT rebuild it.
- Follow existing conventions: `from __future__ import annotations`, module-level `logger`, schema validation via `REQUIRED_*_COLUMNS` dicts + a `_validate_dataframe` helper (see worldcup_playoff/data/loader.py). Pydantic config in config.py loaded from TOML.
- SOLID/TDD: methods <10 lines, classes <50 lines, files <500-600 lines, tests first. Network MUST be mocked in tests (offline). No-key default; football-data.org key optional, from .env (gitignored, repo is public).
- The existing ~248-test suite must stay green; additive changes only.

## Produce
- Component breakdown: each NEW file, public classes/functions with signatures, single responsibilities, dependencies on existing code.
- Data-flow: martj42 raw CSV → internal schema; football-data.org JSON → tournament-state objects; crosswalk usage at the join point.
- Where new Pydantic config sections (e.g. `[martj42]`, `[live]`) and any new CLI commands plug in.
- A phased, dependency-ordered build sequence decomposing the 5 scope items into independent one-session tasks (crosswalk first since loaders depend on it; then schema contracts; then loaders; then bracket-slotting rules), each testable in isolation.
- For each task: files to create/modify, key acceptance checks, and test strategy (mocking network / fixturing CSV & JSON shapes).
Return the blueprint as structured markdown.
