2026-06-23 21:01:10,463 DEBUG msg #260: assistant (tool_use) tool_use(Bash): {'command': 'cd "/Volumes/External SSD/worldcup-2026-prediction" && gh issue create \\\n  --title "feat: WC2026 Round-of-32 bracket-slotting rules (top-2 + 8 best thirds)" \\\n  --milestone "Cycle 1 — Data Loaders & Normalization" \\\n  --label "phase:implement,priority:medium,area:data,agent:python-pro" \\\n  --assignee "@me" \\\n  --body "$(cat <<\'EOF\'\n## Goal\nEncode the official WC2026 Round-of-32 bracket template and the best-third-place selection/assignment rules as pure data + functions, so a later-cycle simulator can deterministically resolve `LAST_32` from final group standings. This is **data and pure rules only — no simulation, no probabilities, no network.**\n\n## Context\nWC2026 has **48 teams → 12 groups**; the top 2 of each group **plus the 8 best third-placed teams** advance to the Round of 32. The football-data.org API returns knockout slot teams as `null` until the groups resolve, so the bracket must be derived, not fetched.\n\nTwo pieces of canonical FIFA data are required:\n1. The **R32 template** — which group-winner (`1A`…`1L`), runner-up (`2A`…`2L`), and best-third placeholder (`3X`) meet in each of the 16 ties.\n2. The **best-third-place assignment table** — a lookup keyed by *which* 8 of the 12 third-placed groups qualified, mapping each third-place placeholder slot to a concrete group. (Same mechanism as the historical 24-team Euro/World Cup third-place tables, expanded for 12 groups / 8 qualifying thirds.)\n\nConsume the `GroupStanding` value object defined in the live adapter (issue #3) as the input type for the resolver. Team names arriving in standings are already canonical via the crosswalk (issue #1), so the resolved pairs need no further normalization. Keep this module a one-way consumer of the `GroupStanding` **type** only — `live.py` must never import this module (avoid cycles).\n\nConventions: module `"""docstring"""` → `from __future__ import annotations` → `logger`; pure functions < 10 lines; frozen module-level data structures. FIFA group-stage tiebreak order for ranking thirds: points, then goal difference, then goals for, then further criteria.\n\n## Agent and skills\n- **Agents:** `python-pro`\n- **Active skills:** `solid-principles`, `python-expert`\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n- [ ] `R32_SLOTS` encodes exactly 16 ties referencing the 24 group-position slots (`1A`–`1L`, `2A`–`2L`) plus 8 third-place placeholders, as a frozen data structure\n- [ ] `THIRD_PLACE_COMBINATIONS` is the official FIFA lookup mapping each valid 8-of-12 qualifying-third combination → slot assignment (or documents the canonical subset it covers)\n- [ ] `rank_third_places(standings) -> list[str]` orders the 12 third-placed teams by FIFA tiebreak (points, GD, GF, …) and returns the qualifying 8 groups, deterministically\n- [ ] `assign_thirds(qualified_third_groups: frozenset[str]) -> dict[str, str]` resolves each `3X` placeholder via the lookup table\n- [ ] `resolve_r32(standings) -> list[tuple[str, str]]` returns 16 concrete `(home, away)` pairs with 32 distinct teams and no duplicates\n- [ ] Pure: importing the module constructs no `FootballClient`, performs no network/randomness; no dependency on martj42 or live HTTP\n- [ ] New symbols exported from `worldcup_playoff/data/__init__.py` + `__all__`\n- [ ] All tests pass\n- [ ] SOLID, clean code (methods < 10 lines, classes < 50 lines, files < 500-600 lines), TDD\n\n## Dependencies\n- #1: feat: team-name crosswalk for martj42 ↔ football-data.org normalization\n- #3: feat: live WC2026 adapter over FootballClient (matches, standings, tournament state)\n\n## Implementation notes\n- **Create:** `worldcup_playoff/data/wc2026_bracket.py` — `GROUPS` (`A`…`L`); a small `SlotRef`/`BracketSlot` type (dataclass or Pydantic) for `1A`/`2C`/`3X` references; `R32_SLOTS` (16 ties); `THIRD_PLACE_COMBINATIONS` lookup; pure functions `rank_third_places`, `assign_thirds`, `resolve_r32`.\n- **Create:** `tests/test_wc2026_bracket.py` — construct a full synthetic 12-group standings list (`GroupStanding` objects); assert `resolve_r32` yields 16 ties / 32 distinct teams and that winners & runners-up land in their template slots; unit-test `assign_thirds` against a couple of known FIFA combination rows; assert no network/`FootballClient` import.\n- **Modify:** `worldcup_playoff/data/__init__.py` — export `resolve_r32`, `R32_SLOTS`, `rank_third_places`, `assign_thirds`; extend `__all__`.\n- Import only the `GroupStanding` type from `live.py` (one-way). Do **not** simulate, sample, or compute probabilities here — that is Cycle 5. Stop at producing `(home, away)` pairs from *given* standings.\nEOF\n)" 2>&1', 'description': 'Create issue 4: bracket-slotting'}
